The process will begin by splitting the data into test and training datasets.

ha_split <- ha %>% initial_split()
# Save test and training as separate datasets
ha_test <- ha_split %>% testing()
ha_train <- ha_split %>% training()
# Check what happened
dim(ha_test)
## [1] 69  8
dim(ha_train)
## [1] 204   8

Q1: KKNN

In this part, we will test models using the KNN

#Creating Model
knn_mod <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = 7) %>%
  set_engine("kknn") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

# add recipe
knn_rec <- recipe(output ~ age + sex + cp + chol + restecg + thalach, data = ha_train) %>%
  step_dummy(sex)  %>% 
  step_dummy(cp) %>% 
  step_dummy(restecg) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric())

# Add workflow
knn_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(knn_rec) %>%
  add_model(knn_mod)

# Fit the model
knn_fit <- knn_wflow %>%
  fit(ha_train)

knn_fit %>% pull_workflow_fit()
## Warning: `pull_workflow_fit()` was deprecated in workflows 0.2.3.
## Please use `extract_fit_parsnip()` instead.
## parsnip model object
## 
## Fit time:  13ms 
## 
## Call:
## kknn::train.kknn(formula = ..y ~ ., data = data, ks = min_rows(7,     data, 5))
## 
## Type of response variable: nominal
## Minimal misclassification: 0.3382353
## Best kernel: optimal
## Best k: 7
#Roc calculation
pred <- knn_fit %>% predict(ha_test, type = "prob")

ha_test <- ha_test %>%
  mutate(
    predicted = pred$.pred_0
  )
roc_auc(ha_test, output, predicted)
## # A tibble: 1 × 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 roc_auc binary         0.821
#Confusion Matrix
pred <- knn_fit %>% predict(ha_test)

ha_test1 <- ha_test %>%
  mutate(
    predicted = pred$.pred_class
  )
ha_test1 %>% count(output, predicted)
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
##   output predicted     n
##   <fct>  <fct>     <int>
## 1 0      0            30
## 2 0      1             7
## 3 1      0             8
## 4 1      1            24

From testing the model and receiving multiple roc.auc values, I was able to conclude that taking out trtbps as one of the predictor variables made the area value higher, alluding to a better model overall.

Q2: Logistic Regression

log_mod <- logistic_reg() %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("glm")

#add recipe
log_rec <- recipe(output ~ age + sex + cp + chol + restecg + thalach, data = ha_train) %>%
  step_dummy(sex)  %>% 
  step_dummy(cp) %>% 
  step_dummy(restecg) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric())

# Add workflow
log_wflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(log_rec) %>%
  add_model(log_mod)

#fit the model
log_fit <- log_wflow%>%
  fit(ha_train)

#Roc calculation
pred <- log_fit %>% predict(ha_test, type = "prob")
ha_test2 <- ha_test %>%
  mutate(
    predicted = pred$.pred_0
  )

Based on an analysis of both models, It appears that age, sex , cp , chol , restecg and thalach all had a positive impact on predicting values given a training set. The only variables that had a negative influence was trtbps, which is the resting blood pressure of an individual.

Part Three: Discussion

Q1

This question can be interpreted as a False Negative. When dealing with trying to minimize false negatives, we would want to use the metric of RECALL. So when choosing which model to use from Part 1, we want to choose the model with the HIGHEST recall value. So based on two of the values, we will go with the KNN MODEL, due to it having a higher recall value. Based on the value we received for the k-fold cross validation we should receive a value around 70 percent.

Q2

This question can be interpreted as minimizing the False positives. In this case, we would use PRECISION as the metric of choice to gauge performance. So when choosing which model to use from Part 1, we want to choose the model with the highest precision value. So based on two of the values we will go with the LOGISTIC MODEL. Based on the value we received for the k-fold cross validation, we should receive a value of around 75 percent. Meaning that 75 percent of the time the prediction will be correct, which is decently high for this model.

Q3

Based on the wording of this question RECALL. You are trying to identify how well the model did at actually predicting heart attack risk. You could also incorporate PRECISION into their analysis, as this identifies the proportion of the predicted target classes that actually do belong to the target class. This usually holds a value similar to that of recall. From these metrics, we can pinpoint the KNN model to be the better option when predicting. And we can also expect a recall value of around 73 percent, and a precision value of right around 73 percent as well.

Q4

Based on the wording of this question, you would want to use PRECISION. Precision deals with positive predictive values, and that is what we want to compare for the doctors and the model output. So we will precision to compare the models. Based on the score that the model received, we can choose the Logistic model as the better model in this case. It received a score of .755 when a k-fold analysis was executed. Since we received this value, we can predict to get a value around this of about 75 percent for the prediction.

Comparing Values

df <- data.frame(
  Model_type = c("Logistic_pre_validation","KNN_pre_validation", "Logistic_validation", "KNN_validation" ), 
  Roc_Auc = c(0.852, 0.804,0.880, 0.852),
  Precision = c(0.756, 0.721, 0.615 ,0.625),
  Recall = c(0.715, 0.707, 0.727, 0.909)
)
datatable(df)

Looking at the data frame above, it is clear that our measure of model success turned out to be correct fir the new validation data. This evident with the higher ROC values (.88 and .85), and better recall rates. While precision took a dip, this could be related to the data itself, as both models performed slightly below the pre_validation scores. What we can deduce from this is that we in fact chose the correct predictor values for our model.
